<HEAD>German Art Has Town Talking, Lawyers Negotiating</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITEWRIGHT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who knew <PERSON>Joe T. Meador</PERSON> say they
can't believe the quiet hardware store owner stole millions in
medieval art from a German church while he was a soldier during
World War II.
   The possibility that <PERSON>Meador</PERSON> stashed the precious cache in a
<LOCATION>Whitewright</LOCATION> bank vault was the talk of this farm town <DATE>Thursday</DATE>,
when The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified sources as saying he
was responsible for one of the century's biggest art thefts.
   ``I just don't believe he was that kind of a man,'' said
73-year-old <PERSON>Mary Bryant</PERSON>, who said she had visited <PERSON>Meador</PERSON>'s home but
could not remember seeing any sumptuous works of art.
   ``He didn't seem the type of guy to me that would do something
like that,'' said <PERSON>Troyce Spencer</PERSON>, who also lives in this town of
1,760 people about 60 miles north of <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION>.
   The newspaper said <PERSON>Meador</PERSON>, in the final days of World War II,
took the objects from a church in <LOCATION>Quedlinburg</LOCATION>, an ancient castle
town in what is now <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>. The Times based its report on
interviews with art experts, lawyers and neighbors of <PERSON>Meador</PERSON>.
   Stolen was a small, silver display case inlaid with enamels and
precious stones, with side panels of carved ivory; a liturgical
ivory comb; a manuscript dated <DATE>1513</DATE>; several rock crystal flasks
and gold and silver crucifixes, and other treasures.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> investigated the theft but dropped the matter in <DATE>1949</DATE>
when Quedlinburg became part of <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Dietrich Kotzsche</PERSON>, a German authority in medieval decorative
art, said the Quedlinburg treasures, dating to the 9th and 10th
centuries, could be worth millions.
   The Times reported today that the church in <LOCATION>Quedlinburg</LOCATION> has
retained two lawyers to seek the return of the art.
   Meador died in <DATE>1980</DATE> at age 64. He co-owned a family hardware and
farm tool business and grew orchids in a greenhouse behind the
two-story Victorian home he shared with his mother, <PERSON>Mabel</PERSON>.
   ``He was the type of fellow that didn't mix with people much,''
said <PERSON>Odell Caraway</PERSON>, a member of <ORGANIZATION>American Legion Post</ORGANIZATION> 225 to which
<PERSON>Meador</PERSON> once belonged. ``As far as I know he's never been involved
in any kind of crooked stuff.''
   <PERSON>Willi A. Korte</PERSON>, a West German government official who
specializes in the repatriation of cultural property, and <PERSON>Thomas R.
Kline</PERSON> of the law firm <ORGANIZATION>Andrews &amp; Kurth</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION>,
said they planned a trip to <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> today to negotiate with <PERSON>Meador</PERSON>'s
relatives, the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Neither those lawyers nor <PERSON>John S. Torigian</PERSON>, an attorney for
<PERSON>Meador</PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON>Jack</PERSON>, could be reached for comment <DATE>Thursday</DATE> by
<ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION>.
   Meador was an officer in the <ORGANIZATION>87th Armored Field Artillery</ORGANIZATION>, which
occupied Quedlinburg and guarded a mine shaft where the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said
the treasures were kept. The items disappeared a few days after
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> troops took over the area in <DATE>1945</DATE>, the newspaper said.
   Three longtime <PERSON>Meador</PERSON> employees said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> they had never
known their boss to show off any art works.
   The Times reported that a source it did not identify said the
treasures are in the vault of the <ORGANIZATION>First National Bank of
Whitewright</ORGANIZATION>, reportedly as collateral for a loan. <PERSON>Harrell Stowers</PERSON>,
the bank's executive vice president, would not confirm that
information <DATE>Thursday</DATE> when asked by <ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Jack Meador</PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON>Jean</PERSON>, and <PERSON>Meador</PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON>Jane Meador
Cook</PERSON>, also would not comment <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   How the treasures got to <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> is a secret that may have died
with <PERSON>Meador</PERSON>.
   Most of the people interviewed <DATE>Thursday</DATE> said they didn't know
<PERSON>Meador</PERSON> had even been in the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> or World War II.
   ``We haven't had this much excitement since the machine gun
deal,'' said Mayor <PERSON>Clarence Tillet Jr.</PERSON>, who explained that a judge
once charged four machine guns in the town's name to avoid paying
sales tax.
</TEXT>
