<HEAD>East German Church To Get Help With Missing Treasures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUD S. BEELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An East German church is getting help
from <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> to retrieve art treasures believed pilfered by an
American soldier at the close of World War II, a West German
official said <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   East and <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> also agreed to build an information
database aimed at the return of other art works that vanished when
the Third <PERSON>Reich</PERSON> fell.
   Litigation to retrieve the so-called Quedlinburg treasures from
bank vaults in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> is already under way. The <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION>
said <DATE>Monday</DATE> that <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> would pay the legal costs.
   <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>'s help in meeting the expense will be a major boost for the
<ORGANIZATION>Lutheran Church of Quedlinburg</ORGANIZATION>, which claims its treasures were
stolen at the end of World War II, said <PERSON>Klaus Maurice</PERSON>, director of
the <ORGANIZATION>West German Cultural Foundation</ORGANIZATION> of the States.
   ``Nobody knew until now who had to pay, but they will pay and
this is marvelous,'' <PERSON>Maurice</PERSON> said.
   The Quedlinburg treasures include two rare medieval manuscripts,
a jeweled, ivory-carved container for relics and several
rock-crystal and ivory objects. They were allegedly removed from a
mine shaft where they had been hidden in the final days of the war.
   <PERSON>Maurice</PERSON> said there was no doubt the art works in question were
authentic.
   The Quedlinburg treasures, among <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>'s most famous art
works, were allegedly taken by a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> army officer stationed in
<LOCATION>Quedlinburg</LOCATION>, now <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>, in <DATE>1945</DATE>, and brought to his hometown
of <LOCATION>Whitewright</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>.
   The church is suing the sister and brother of the officer, the
late <PERSON>Joe T. Meador</PERSON>, to recover the treasures.
   <PERSON>Maurice</PERSON> said officials have no clear idea of how many other
works were allegedly looted from <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>'s artitistic heritage in
the final months of the war.
   ``The problem up to now is that we had two states and it wasn't
easy to speak with <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Maurice</PERSON> said. ``Now, this is
easier.''
   Maurice spoke after attending a two-hour meeting to dicuss
coordinated approaches toward retrieving lost German art. Also
attending the meeting was a <ORGANIZATION>Ministry of Culture</ORGANIZATION> representative from
<LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>, which is expected to formally unite with its Western
neighbor in <DATE>December</DATE>.
   The new database is to be established in <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> and collect
information from museums, churches and other institutions
throughout the two Germanys, <PERSON>Maurice</PERSON> said. The database will
compare pre-World War II inventories with current records in an
attempt to get a complete picture of what is missing, he said.
</TEXT>
