<HEAD>Army: Records of Stolen Art Probe Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENISON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> said it has thrown out all
records of its investigation into the World War II theft of German
medieval artworks that wound up in a small town in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>.
   As a result, the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> may never know whether a former soldier
from <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> who died in <DATE>1980</DATE> was a suspect in the theft, an <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>
spokeswoman told <ORGANIZATION>The Denison Herald</ORGANIZATION> in an interview published
<DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   The artifacts, some of them stored in the vault of the <ORGANIZATION>First
National Bank</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Whitewright</LOCATION>, have been valued in the <MONEY>millions of
dollars</MONEY> by German art experts.
   A Lutheran church in <LOCATION>Quedlinburg</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>, is suing to
recover the artwork from the bank and the late <PERSON>Joe T. Meador</PERSON>'s
family.
   Meador is believed to have stolen the objects while an <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>
lieutenant, and stashed them in his hometown about 60 miles north
of <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION>. He left the artifacts to a brother and sister.
   Army military police investigated the theft, but the file was
apparently destroyed in <DATE>1964</DATE> when records of all cases older than
15 years were purged, <PERSON>Barbara Parker</PERSON>, a spokeswoman at the <ORGANIZATION>U.S.
Army Crime Records Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Fort Holabird</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Md.</LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION>Herald</ORGANIZATION>.
   Only records of historical interest survived the housecleaning,
<PERSON>Parker</PERSON> said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> abandoned the case in <DATE>1949</DATE> when Quedlinburg became part
of <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>. Army spokesmen have said it is unclear whether the
military will reopen the case.
   The articles allegedly taken by <PERSON>Meador</PERSON> include a silver, ivory
and gold reliquary from the 9th or <DATE>10th century</DATE>, a 10th century
Byzantine rock-crystal flask with sides formed like birds and an
ivory comb inlaid with precious stones.
   Meador's heirs, <PERSON>Jack Meador</PERSON>, 70, and <PERSON>Jane Cook</PERSON>, 58, said <DATE>earlier
this week</DATE> that their unoccupied farmhouse was ransacked <DATE>Monday</DATE>
<TIME>night</TIME> by burglars who mistakenly believed the treasure was there.
   The burglary was described in a motion filed by <PERSON>Meador</PERSON> and <PERSON>Ms.
Cook</PERSON> seeking a protective order to keep all parties in the lawsuit
from discussing the case in public. <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> District <PERSON>Judge Sidney A.
Fitzwater</PERSON> denied the motion <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   The bank had acknowledged the artifacts are in the vault.
Fitzwater has ordered the bank to allow representatives of the
church to inventory and photograph the artifacts.
   Denison is 70 miles north of <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
